# Cursor Rules for Nevada License Defense Website

## Project Context
- This is a Next.js 14+ website built with TypeScript and Tailwind CSS
- Professional law firm website for Nevada License Defense
- Focus on clean, maintainable, and performant code

## Visual Website Style
- Sans serif fonts, incorporating bold lettering
- Use the following hex code colors; Dark Blue: #12203bff Light Gold: #f0c563ff Dark Gold: #b27e4fff Brown: #6D5D49
- The provided hex colors are a part of the logo; Dark Blue is the base of the logo, so Dark Blue cannot be used behind the logo file
- Do not use the lighter gold color (#f0c563ff) for any text that is on top of a white background - the visibility and contrast is poor
- Incorporate visual ease animations on elements to provide a sophisticated, modern look

## Visual Hierarchy Rules
- Use equal column sizes when creating multi-column layouts for visual balance
- Maintain consistent spacing and alignment across similar elements
- Ensure visual balance in grid layouts - avoid lopsided or uneven column distributions

## Code Style Preferences

### TypeScript/React
- Use TypeScript for all new files
- Prefer functional components with hooks over class components
- Use explicit type annotations for function parameters and return types
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Use `'use client'` directive only when necessary (for hooks, event handlers, etc.)

### Component Organization
- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Place reusable components in `components/ui/`
- Place page-specific components in `components/sections/`
- Use default exports for components
- Co-locate component styles with components when possible

### Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes
- Prefer Tailwind over custom CSS when possible
- Use CSS variables for theme colors defined in `tailwind.config.js`
- Keep custom CSS in `app/globals.css` minimal
- Use responsive design (mobile-first approach)

### File Naming
- Use kebab-case for file names: `contact-form.tsx`
- Use PascalCase for component names: `ContactForm`
- Use descriptive, clear names

### Code Quality
- Write self-documenting code with clear variable names
- Add comments only when logic is complex or non-obvious
- Prefer early returns over nested conditionals
- Use async/await over promises when possible
- Handle errors gracefully with try/catch

### Next.js Specific
- Use App Router (not Pages Router)
- Use Server Components by default, Client Components only when needed
- Use Next.js Image component for images
- Use Next.js Link component for internal navigation
- Implement proper SEO with metadata in layout.tsx and page.tsx

### Performance
- Optimize images before adding to project
- Use dynamic imports for heavy components
- Minimize bundle size
- Use React.memo() sparingly, only when profiling shows it's needed

### Accessibility
- Always include alt text for images
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Ensure proper heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3)
- Include ARIA labels when needed
- Ensure keyboard navigation works

### Git/Version Control
- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Don't commit node_modules, .next, or build files
- Keep commits focused on single features/fixes

## Communication Style
- Explain complex decisions briefly
- Suggest improvements when appropriate
- Point out potential issues or better alternatives
- Be concise but thorough

## When Making Changes
- Preserve existing functionality unless explicitly asked to change it
- Update related files if making structural changes
- Check for linting errors after changes
- Ensure responsive design still works after changes

## Testing Considerations
- Write code that's easy to test (though we're not writing tests yet)
- Keep components pure when possible
- Avoid side effects in render functions

## Development Workflow
- **ALWAYS start the development server when Cursor resets/reopens or when beginning a new session**
- Run `npm run dev` (or use the VS Code task "Start Dev Server") to start the local development server
- The server should be running on `http://localhost:3000` before making changes that need to be previewed
- If the server is not running, start it immediately at the beginning of any coding session


